Phase 2 — Add the column existence check before Loop App Rows
Now we need to add a Condition that validates the Excel file has the Org Unit Display Name column BEFORE the loop runs. This is Option 3 — fail-fast at file boundary, before processing 100s of rows.
Where it goes: Inside App Header Valid → If Yes (which is the existing branch that contains Loop App Rows). Specifically, it goes ABOVE the existing Loop App Rows action — and Loop App Rows ends up moved INSIDE the new condition.
This is a slightly tricky operation in Power Automate because we need to "wrap" an existing action inside a new Condition. Let me give you the exact steps.
Step 2.1 — Add the new Condition above Loop App Rows
In Power Automate, navigate to:

Section 8: APP FILE EXISTS
Inside it: App File Exists condition

If Yes branch

Set variable 5 (existing)
Read App Excel (existing)
App Header Valid (existing — the existing condition checking for "Display Name")

If Yes branch ← we are working inside here

Loop App Rows (existing — this is what we'll wrap)


If No branch (existing — Warn App Invalid Header)







Inside App Header Valid → If Yes, currently the only thing is Loop App Rows. We're inserting our new Condition above it.

Inside App Header Valid → If Yes, click the + icon ABOVE Loop App Rows (between the "If yes" header and the Loop App Rows action) → Add an action
Search for Condition → select Condition (Control)
Rename it (click the title):

App Has Org Unit Column

Configure the condition row:

Left value — click the field, switch to fx (Expression), paste:
contains(string(first(body('Read_App_Excel')?['value'])), 'Org Unit Display Name')
Operator: is equal to
Right value — click fx, type:
true

Don't fill the If Yes / If No branches yet

Confirm: New App Has Org Unit Column Condition appears ABOVE Loop App Rows, with the contains() expression on the left.
Step 2.2 — Move Loop App Rows INTO the If Yes branch
Now we need to relocate Loop App Rows from where it currently sits to inside the new condition's If Yes branch.
In Power Automate, the cleanest way to "move" an action is cut + paste:

Click the ⋯ (three-dot menu) on the Loop App Rows action header
Select Cut
Click into the If Yes branch of App Has Org Unit Column
Click the + Add an action placeholder inside If Yes
At the top of the action picker, you should see My clipboard as a tab — click it
Paste Loop App Rows

If "Cut/My clipboard" isn't available in your Power Automate version, alternative: delete and re-add is too destructive (we'd lose the entire 60+ action loop body). In that case, STOP and tell me — we'll use a different approach (collapse the loop body into a Scope, or rebuild the parent condition differently).
Step 2.3 — Fill the If No branch with the warning
Inside App Has Org Unit Column → If No:

Click + Add an action
Search for Append to string variable → select it
Rename:

Warn App Missing Org Unit Column

Configure:

Name: Select varWarnings from dropdown
Value:
App file is missing 'Org Unit Display Name' column. BU resolution skipped for all apps. Verify LeanIX export template includes this column.

Confirm when:

App Has Org Unit Column Condition exists in the right place
Loop App Rows is now INSIDE the If Yes branch (not at the parent level anymore)
Warn App Missing Org Unit Column is inside If No
Loop App Rows is intact — all the actions that were inside it (Reset varAppOwningBU, Valid Owner App, etc.) are still there

